WEBVTT

00:00:00.400 --> 00:00:03.000
I see the comment about money is what matters when it comes to

00:00:03.000 --> 00:00:06.600
executives. I really do think understanding executives is a

00:00:06.600 --> 00:00:13.120
fascinating undertaking. Like just thinking about preparing

00:00:13.120 --> 00:00:17.280
graphs that executives are going to present or consume. I once

00:00:17.320 --> 00:00:21.200
told someone on my team long ago, like, he actually wrote a

00:00:21.200 --> 00:00:23.920
function called execufy. And like, basically, this needs to

00:00:23.920 --> 00:00:27.000
take the graphs we have, and make it look like they were

00:00:27.000 --> 00:00:32.680
drawn with a crayon, like, simple, big, you know, and, and

00:00:32.680 --> 00:00:35.040
that's the kind of thing that often gets in the executive

00:00:35.040 --> 00:00:38.840
level, communications. And then the question is why, because

00:00:38.840 --> 00:00:42.240
sometimes it seems like it gets dumbed down the higher it goes.

00:00:42.520 --> 00:00:46.840
But executives are generally very sharp people, many of whom

00:00:46.840 --> 00:00:50.360
have come from very detailed technical backgrounds, right. So

00:00:50.360 --> 00:00:53.799
it's not about the people, it's about the responsibilities they

00:00:53.799 --> 00:00:56.720
have and the perspective they have. And I think really trying

00:00:56.720 --> 00:01:01.439
to understand that is really helpful in thinking about how to

00:01:01.439 --> 00:01:04.599
support them in running the business. And they do care about

00:01:04.599 --> 00:01:08.080
money, which can be frustrating, but is also really important if

00:01:08.080 --> 00:01:12.559
you want to stay employed and work for a company that has

00:01:12.559 --> 00:01:15.120
money to spend on data scientists and stays in

00:01:15.120 --> 00:01:19.239
business. So it's somebody has to care about that. And we have

00:01:19.239 --> 00:01:21.919
to support them in some way and doing their jobs.

